<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Finding 6 · SSRF</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <div class="brand brand-sm" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">🌐</div>
      <h1>Finding 6 confirmed</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">Day 6 · Server-Side Request Forgery</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📚</div>
        <h2>The vulnerability</h2>
        <h3>The server fetches what you tell it to</h3>
        <p>Any feature that takes a user-supplied URL and fetches it server-side is potentially SSRF. The server has different network reach and different headers than you do. Including access to internal-only services, cloud metadata endpoints, and any auth your code adds "automatically."</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📰</div>
        <h2>Seen in the wild</h2>
        <h3>Capital One · 2019</h3>
        <p>SSRF in a misconfigured WAF allowed an attacker to query AWS instance metadata at <code>169.254.169.254</code>, steal IAM credentials, and exfiltrate 100M+ customer records. $190M settlement. Modern SSRF is one of the highest-impact bug classes in cloud environments.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🛠️</div>
        <h2>How to fix it</h2>
        <h3>Allow-list, not deny-list</h3>
        <p>Validate URLs against an explicit allow-list of domains. Block private IP ranges (RFC1918, loopback, link-local). Use a dedicated service account with no internal network access. Never propagate "trusted internal" headers to user-controlled destinations. Use IMDSv2 on AWS.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>One-line takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Your server is a confused deputy</h3>
        <p>SSRF turns your backend into a proxy for the attacker. With your network position, your credentials, and your trust. Anywhere the server can reach, the attacker can now reach through you.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All findings</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %><a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Day <%= nextNum %> →</a><% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
